1. e4 e5
{ Welcome to this full course on 1.e4 e5. In this Introduction, we will see a quick overview of all the lines covered and I will briefly explain every one of them. }
2. Nf3
{ 2.Nc3  Against Nc3 and Bc4 my recommendation is to go for the natural development: knights on c6 and f6, bishop on c5.  2...Nc6  3.Bc4   3.g3  Bc5  Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  We will study some sidelines like, for example, 5.f4 and the most standard 5.Nc3 transposing to an Italian.   2.Bc4  After Nf6 and Nc6 we will transpose to 2.Nc3 or to an Italian.  2...Nf6  3.d3  Nc6  4.Nc3   4.Nf3  Bc5  5.c3  Bc5   2.f4  Against the King's Gambit, my recommendation is one of the most solid choices for Black, which offers us a fine position without unnecessary complications.  2...d5  3.exd5  exf4  4.Nf3  Nf6  Black will go for normal development and White does not get the kind of messy position he is going after.   2.d4  Against this move we will simply examine the most popular reply, which offers Black a fine position.  2...exd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  Followed by natural development moves: Nf6, Bb4, O-O, and so on. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ 3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bb5   4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4  Bb4  Here we will examine the main line, a smooth equalizer where Black does not need to worry in any line.  Bb4  I like this move, rather than playing 5...Nd4. Very often Black will get an easy game with a symmetrical position and this move somewhat limits White's choice more than 5...Nd4.   3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  Here we will examine the most aggressive option, undoubtedly the most challenging for White. These positions will be quite complex and we will analyze them in detail.  5.Nxc6  bxc6  6.e5  Qe7  7.Qe2  Nd5  8.c4  Ba6  Of course, we will study some alternatives for White along the way. Against the main line with 8.c4 I like 8...Ba6, one of Black's main moves. I have successfully played it myself.   3.Bc4  Bc5  I like this move, rather than playing 3...Nf6 and allow 4.Ng5 with extremely complicated positions.  4.c3  Nf6  Here White has a choice between a solid approach with 5.d3 or the aggressive 5.d4. In any case, we will examine thoroughly both options and I will show you lines that, in my opinion, are quite challenging for White.  5.d3   5.d4  exd4  d6 }
3... a6 4. Ba4
{ 4.Bxc6  dxc6  5.O-O  Qf6  Against the Spanish Exchange I suggest this move. It is not the main line, but strong players like Caruana have used this move and it leads to unbalanced positions where it is easier for Black to play for a win. }
4... Nf6 5. O-O
{ 5.d3  Bc5  I like this move, rather than playing 5...b5 which offers White more options to play a4 and quickly put some pressure on the queenside. We will examine how to play against White's normal setup c3 + d4 and against Bxc6. }
5... Nxe4
{ The starting point of the Open Spanish. In general, this is an aggressive variation aiming at complicated positions. In my practical experience, I would say it is quite challenging for White and it is easy for Black to obtain some advantage if our opponent does not know well the resulting positions. From here on we will study almost everything in quite depth. }
*

