[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "King's Gambit, 5.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The main line is  2...exf4  , but in my opinion this move is simpler and equally good. }
3. exd5
{ Of course  3.fxe5  is not playable due to  3...Qh4  winning. After  3.Nf3  exf4  White has nothing better than transposing to the main line with exd5. }
3... exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Here White has some alternatives, but none seems particularly challenging for Black. If the knight captures on d5, Black will get an excellent position. }
5. Bc4 { White offers up a pawn to speed development, but it is not enough. }
5... Nxd5 6. O-O Be6
{ An important move: Black protects d5, indirectly threatens the c4-bishop @@StartBracket@@  7.d4  is not possible due to  7...Ne3  followed by Bxc4 @@EndBracket@@ , covers the e-file and in some lines prepares to castle queenside. }
7. Bb3
{ The most dangerous reply, stopping any Ne3 tricks and preparing d4 and c4. Black needs to rely on some tactics here, so it is important to know this line. }
7... Nc6 8. d4 Qf6
{ Unsurprisingly, this move works well. Black has good development and is just one move away from castling queenside. }
9. c4 Ne3 10. Bxe3 fxe3 11. d5 { The only try. } 11... Qxb2 12. dxe6 fxe6 13.
Qc2
{ The only move to 'guard' the rook. If  13...Qxa1  14.Nc3  winning the queen. }
13... Qxc2 { White succeeds in trading queens. } 14. Bxc2
{ Black has three pawns for the sacrificed piece. The e3-pawn is strong and the dark-squared bishop is unopposed. Still, we should have a closer look to secure an almost winning position. Let's see the most precise play for both sides. }
14... g5
{ This threatens ...Bg7 capturing the rook and tries to kick the white knight away from f3 to get the d4-square. The following sequence is practically forced for White to avoid an immediate disaster. }
15. a3 O-O-O 16. Nxg5 Nd4 17. Be4 e2 18. Re1 Bc5 19. Kh1 Bb6
{ Followed by ...Ba5. Black will get the piece back with a huge advantage in the endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "King's Gambit, 5.c4#"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The main line is  2...exf4  , but in my opinion this move is simpler and equally good. }
3. exd5
{ Of course  3.fxe5  is not playable due to  3...Qh4  winning. After  3.Nf3  exf4  White has nothing better than transposing to the main line with  4.exd5  . }
3... exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Here White has some alternatives, but none seems particularly challenging for Black. If the knight captures on d5, Black will get an excellent position. }
5. c4 { Perhaps the best option. Even Carlsen has played this! } 5... c6
{ Again Black surrenders the pawn for good to speed development. } 6. dxc6
{ A weak move, just speeding Black's development. Let's see how we can counter it. }
6... Nxc6
{ If Black takes control of d4 the game is over, so White's play is practically forced. }
7. d4 Bg4 8. Be2
{ At this point this is the best choice, but it drops d4 and White loses its grip in the center. }
8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nxd4 10. O-O
{ Instead,  10.Bxb7  Qe7  was not an option, as Black is winning. } 10... Bc5
11. Kh1 g5
{ Once again the f4-pawn blunts the c1-bishop. Black has a huge advantage. For example, }
12. Bxb7 Rb8 13. Bf3 O-O 14. Nc3 Re8 { Black dominates the whole board. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Scotch, 6.Qe2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  would transpose to theFour Knights. } 5... bxc6 6. Qe2
{ A rare move, but still important to know. } 6... Rb8
{ Black has some alternatives, but I like this move. We put some pressure on b2 and control the b4-square. This is an important square for Black's pieces, as we will see. }
7. e5 Nd5 8. c4 { If  8.Nd2  we simply play  8...Be7  intending ...O-O. } 8...
Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Nf4
{ Now the power of the rook on b8 becomes apparent: it covers the b4-bishop and applies some indirect pressure on b2. }
10. Qe3 Ng6
{ Black will play ...O-O and ...Re8 next to put pressure on e5, with a great position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Scotch, 10.g3 Bg7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  would transpose to theFour Knights. } 5... bxc6 6. e5
{ The main move. } 6... Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4 Ba6
{ Exploiting the pin.  8...Nb6  is also possible. } 9. b3 g6
{ This is the main position in this line. White has different moves here and they are all dangerous. }
10. g3 { This move leads almost by force to a well-known endgame. } 10... Bg7
11. Bb2 O-O 12. Bg2 Rae8 { 12...Rfe8  is similar. } 13. O-O Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxe5
15. Qxe5 Rxe5 16. cxd5 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 cxd5 18. Nc3 { 18.Na3  is similar. } 18...
c6
{ And we have reached this unbalanced yet equal endgame. Black has a rook and two pawns, whereas White has a knight and a bishop. I will analyze this position in more detail in the video. Here's an overview of the most important ideas:  • We need to centralize our king; d6 is usually a good square.  • We should trade one rook if possible, and we should not allow White's rook to comfortably reach the a6-square. How? Either by threatening a rook invasion through the e-file or by pushing ...a5 and placing a rook on a8. Then White's rook would stand on the not so annoying a4-square. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Scotch, 5.O-O d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 { The famous Scotch Gambit. } 4... Bc5
{ Here the main line is by far  5.c3  and after  5...Nf6  we would transpose to the c3-d4 Italian, which will be covered inanother section. That is why I prefer playing this, rather than  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/2BpP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , which is the main option. As we will need to study this line anyway against the Italian, it makes no sense at all to learn 4...Nf6 as well. Fully learning one line is better than half-learning two! Let us check the two alternatives we need to be well prepared against. }
5. O-O d6 6. c3 Bg4
{ An important move, preventing the capture on d4 and stopping White's development. }
7. Qb3
{ The only way to fight for some initiative. Keep in mind White is a pawn down. }
7... Bxf3 8. Bxf7+
{ If  8.gxf3  we simply play  8...Ne5  , protecting f7 and hitting both f3 and the c4-bishop. Black has a good position. }
8... Kf8 9. gxf3 Nf6 10. Bc4 Qe8
{ Black has better development and good attacking chances on the kingside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Four Knights, 4.Bb5 Bb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ The two main moves here are by far  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  . The most played alternatives are  4.Bc4  , which we will examine in theItalian section, and  4.g3  , which will be briefly covered here. I will show you a simple plan for Black. }
4. Bb5 Bb4 { 4...Nd4  is another fine alternative. } 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 d6
{ So far, standard piece development for both sides. Now there are two possible approaches for White. }
7. Bg5 { The most aggressive. } 7... Ne7
{ Bxf6 is not scary, as both the knight on e7 and the bishop on c8 are covering the f5-square and so White cannot exploit it. }
8. Bxf6 gxf6 9. Nh4 c6 10. Bc4
{ 10.Ba4  can be met by  10...a5  and the white bishop lands in some trouble. }
10... Ng6 11. Nf5 d5
{ Black uses the fact that White can never play  12.exd5  due to  12...Bxf5  . }
12. Bb3 a5
{ Black can conveniently play ...Bxf5 and the white bishop will be pointless on b3, just staring at d5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Four Knights, 4.g3 Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ The two main moves here are by far  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  . The most played alternatives are  4.Bc4  , which we will examine in theItalian section, and  4.g3  , which will be briefly covered here. I will show you a simple plan for Black. }
4. g3 Bc5 { The bishop stands better on this diagonal than fianchettoed. } 5.
Bg2 d6 6. d3 a5 { Preventing the Na4 idea, trading the bishop. } 7. O-O O-O 8.
h3
{ The only decent plan for White is to try to play f4. Therefore, the white king has to step away from g1 first. }
8... a4 { Gaining space on the queenside and threatening ...a3 in some lines. }
9. a3 { White has to play this move sooner or later. } 9... h6 10. Kh2 Be6
{ Black is ready to break on d5 if needed. } 11. Nh4 Nd4
{ 11...d5  was not that good, as the white knight would get a nice spot on f5 after all the trades. White is not threatening f4 now, though. }
12. f4 exf4 13. gxf4 Nxe4 { Followed by ...Qxh4 winning. } *

