[Black "Four Knights, 4.d4 exd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5
{ This sacrifice does not trouble us, but still it is worth knowing. } 5... Nb4
{ A strange move, but totally sensible. Black is trying to get rid of the d5-knight on their terms. }
6. Nxf6+
{ If Black manages ...Nbxd5 their position will be great, so this looks like the best try. }
6... Qxf6 7. Bc4 Bc5 8. O-O d6
{ Black has nothing to fear, as castle comes next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Italian Sidelines, Evans Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans Gambit! Not a usual sight nowadays, but good to know how to handle it. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Be7
{ Recently, the most usual move, with good reason. Black sidesteps the sharpest lines and simply wants to return the pawn to develop quickly. }
6. d4 Na5
{ An important move, kicking the bishop away from c4. Black offers the e5-pawn to get some initiative. }
7. Bd3 d6 { Black gives the pawn back to speed development. } 8. dxe5 dxe5 9.
Nxe5 Nf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2
{ Other moves do not change much in the position. For example,  11.Qe2  Re8  with a similar position. }
11... Bd6
{ Black has several options here. This is perhaps the most straightforward continuation. }
12. Nf3 Bg4 { Attacking the knight again. } 13. Nbd2 Re8
{ Thus Black has prevented the development of the c1-bishop. } 14. h3 Bh5 15.
Re1 Nd7
{ Controlling e5 and heading to c5, an excellent outpost for Black's pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Italian, Sidelines #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6
{ We will now examine some lines that are not that usual in current tournament practice. However, they are still reasonable choices and played from time to time. }
6. b4
{ Gaining some space on the queenside. The flip side is some weakening and more potential breakthroughs for Black. }
6... Bb6 7. a4 a5
{ White cannot be allowed to push a5, as that would trap the b6-bishop. } 8. b5
Ne7 { The knight is heading to g6 again. } 9. O-O O-O 10. Nbd2
{ White intends to regroup this knight to c4 to hit the b6-bishop, so Black takes some preemptive measures. }
10... Ng6 11. Bb3 c6
{ Freeing c7 for the bishop, intending the d5 push and creating some tension on b5. }
12. Nc4 Bc7 13. Re1
{ Only move to stop ...d5. Now the e5-pawn would be hanging. } 13... cxb5
{ There are other interesting options, but this move poses some problems for White. }
14. axb5 Bd7 { Suddenly, b5 is a weakness. } 15. b6 Bxb6 16. Nxd6 Qc7
{ Attacking d6 and c3.  16...Bxf2  17.Kxf2  followed by  17...Qb6  18.d4  and  18...Qxd6  looked good, but it does not work, as White has  19.Ba3  at the end of the line, winning the f8-rook. }
17. Ba3
{ Now  17...Qxc3  is not possible because of  18.Rc1  and the queen is trapped. }
17... a4 18. Ba2
{ Avoiding  18...Qxc3  19.Nc4  and again the black queen would be trapped. }
18... Bc5 19. Bxc5 Qxc5 { This bishop trade leaves the d6-knight hanging. } 20.
Nxf7
{ White offers two pieces for the rook, but picking up some pawns in the process and weakening Black's king. }
20... Rxf7 21. Ng5 Be8 22. Bxf7+ Bxf7 23. Nxf7 Kxf7 24. Rxa4
{ This is White's idea. White has managed to get rid of Black's passed a-pawn. }
24... Rxa4 25. Qxa4 Qxc3
{ I think Black has better chances, but Black's king is exposed and some careful play is required. }
26. Qa2+ Kf8 27. Rb1 Nf4
{ White's rook is not easy to activate, as a back rank check would be deadly. Therefore, Black can try to put their king to safety and regroup their knights. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Italian, Sidelines #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6
{ We will now examine some lines that are not that usual in current tournament practice. However, they are still reasonable choices and played from time to time. }
6. O-O a5 7. Bb3
{ The point of this move is a potential regroup of the bishop to c2 and then pushing d4. It is more natural when Black plays 6...a6, but we should know how to handle it here as well. That will help us understand these positions. }
7... O-O 8. Re1 Be6
{ Black is happy to trade these bishops, as the position would be simplified and easier to play for Black. Therefore, retreating the b3-bishop is the most sensible option for White. }
9. Bc2 Ng4 { Hitting f2 and forcing White to lose a tempo. } 10. d4
{ This natural move fails to some tactics. } 10... exd4 11. cxd4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4
Qh4 { With a double attack on h2 and f2 that wins the game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Italian, 5.d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4
{ This move is still often played nowadays, so it is essential for Black to know it well. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4
{ This move is less and less seen, as it appears that Black is fine in the main lines. }
6... Bb4+ 7. Nc3
{ White sacrifices the e4-pawn to get some extra tempi, but Black is just one move away from castling, so White's compensation is insufficient. }
7... Nxe4 8. O-O Bxc3 9. d5
{ This is White's idea. After  9.bxc3  d5  , Black has a healthy extra pawn. }
9... Bf6
{ White will get the piece back. However, Black will be perfectly fine if they can safely castle. }
10. Re1
{ After  10.dxc6  bxc6  , Black will play ...d5 supporting e4, with a huge advantage. }
10... Ne7 11. Rxe4 d6
{ 11...O-O  is also possible, but Black can take some time to prevent the d6 push first. }
12. g4 { A desperate attempt to disturb Black's position. } 12... O-O 13. g5
Be5 { Black returns the pawn and will now target White's kingside weaknesses. }
14. Nxe5 Bf5 { A cool intermediate move, gaining a tempo on the rook. } 15. Re1
dxe5 16. Rxe5 Qd7
{ Material is equal, but Black's position is much better, as White's king is exposed. White wishes the g-pawn were back on g2 instead of g5. }
*

