[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Italian, 5.d4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4
{ This move is still often played nowadays, so it is essential for Black to know it well. }
5... exd4 6. e5 d5 7. Bb5 { The main move. } 7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. Nc3 O-O
10. Be3 { It is important for White to keep the d4-pawn well protected. } 10...
Bg4 { Pinning the f3-knight, in charge of the defense of d4 and e5. } 11. h3
Bh5
{ Now  12.Qc2  is by far the most played move, but I will examine some alternatives. Despite not being so popular, these moves are interesting as well and worth knowing. }
12. Qc2 Ba5
{ This move has recently become very popular. Black pins the c3-knight and forces matters. }
13. Bxc6
{ White's idea is to avoid the main line we will examine later but, as we know, trading this bishop has some downsides as well. }
13... bxc6 14. O-O Bxc3 15. bxc3 f5
{ Black's minor pieces are better coordinated and Black has good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
16. Nd2
{ After  16.exf6  Bxf3  followed by Nxf6 Black's position is very fine. } 16...
f4 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Bc1 Bg6
{ Black has a strong pawn pair on e4 and f4 and can launch an attack with ideas like a queen jump to g5 or h4 and a rook lift via f5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Italian, Main lines #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O a5
{ Stopping White's b4-expansion and freeing the a7-square for the bishop to stay out of harm's way. }
7. Re1 O-O
{ White's plan is regrouping the b1-knight to g3 and try to push d4. This may or may not include playing h3. }
8. Nbd2 Ba7 { Pre-empting a potential d4 push. } 9. Nf1 Be6
{ Black wants to trade bishops and now White is forced to make an important decision. }
10. Bxe6 { This is a double-edged move and not all White players' cup of tea. }
10... fxe6
{ Black has doubled pawns, but now the f -file is open so that the rook and the a7-bishop launch an excellent combined attack against f2. Black will enjoy very active piece play. }
11. Ng3 a4
{ Again Black gains some space and takes the b3-square away from White's queen. }
12. h3 { Preventing an eventual Ng4. } 12... h6 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Rxe3 d5
{ Black gets to break first, thanks to the unfortunate situation of the rook on e3. }
15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Re4 a3
{ Of course Black's e5-e6 structure is very weak, but Black has provoked some serious weaknesses on the queenside: b2-c3 and d3 are weak. Also, if White's queen tries to protect them, then Rxf3 becomes an option. This is a thematic sacrifice that destroys White's castle and offers Black a great game. }
*

