[Black "Italian, Main lines #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O a5
{ Stopping White's b4-expansion and freeing the a7-square for the bishop to stay out of harm's way. }
7. Re1 O-O
{ White's plan is regrouping the b1-knight to g3 and try to push d4. This may or may not include playing h3. }
8. Nbd2 Ba7 { Pre-empting a potential d4 push. } 9. Nf1 Be6
{ Black wants to trade bishops and now White is forced to make an important decision. }
10. Bxe6 { This is a double-edged move and not all White players' cup of tea. }
10... fxe6
{ Black has doubled pawns, but now the f -file is open so that the rook and the a7-bishop launch an excellent combined attack against f2. Black will enjoy very active piece play. }
11. Ng3 a4
{ Again Black gains some space and takes the b3-square away from White's queen. }
12. h3 { Preventing an eventual Ng4. } 12... h6 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Rxe3 d5
{ Black gets to break first, thanks to the unfortunate situation of the rook on e3. }
15. Re1 d4
{ Gaining some central space and blocking the e-file for good, so the e5-pawn is not so weak anymore. }
16. Rc1 { 16.cxd4  exd4  does not change much. } 16... Nd7 17. cxd4 exd4
{ White has neither a clear plan nor targets on sight, whereas Black can improve their position by playing Qe7 intending Qb4 or Nc5. }
18. Ne2
{ Putting pressure on d4 and intending to force ...e5 and thus obtain the f5-square. }
18... Rxf3
{ This is a thematic sacrifice we should always take into account whenever the queen stops protecting f3. }
19. gxf3 Qg5+
{ White's king is exposed and Black can use the e5-square for the knight to join the attack. Black's rook can also come to f8 at any moment. }
20. Kh1
{ Against both  20.Kh2  and  20.Ng3  Black can reply  20...Nde5  with a nice attacking position. }
20... Qh5 21. Ng1 Rf8
{ With an excellent position. Black's knight can join the attack via e5, whereas the white rooks lack open files to be relevant. }
