Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3
{ The main line. White aims to get a knight into d4 by knocking on e6 and c6. }
12... Qd7 { Defending c6 and e6 and connecting rooks. } 13. Nfd4
{ 13.Nbd4  is more usual, but after  13...Nxd4  14.Nxd4  it transposes to the main line and also gives Black an extra option:  13...Nd8  , so more and more players are going for this move. }
13... Nxd4
{ 13...Nxe5  was not possible due to  14.f3  followed by Re1 and Black has too many pieces on the e-file. }
14. Nxd4
{ After  14.cxd4  a5  , White has no way to stop a4 kicking the b3-knight. }
14... c5 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3
{ If White does not expel this knight now, Black can follow up with ...c4 intending Nc5. }
16... Ng5 17. a4
{ Black has everything defended in the center, so White needs this plan to create some problems. After  17.Kh1  f4  , White has nothing better than  18.a4  back to the main line. }
17... Rad8 { Black gives up the file but in return defends his center better. }
18. axb5 axb5 19. Qe2 { Threatening the b5-pawn. } 19... c4 20. Be3 Qc6
{ Black is ready to follow up with ...Ne6 and gets the desired formation. } *

