1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The main line is  2...exf4  , but in my opinion, this move is simpler and equally good. }
3. exd5
{ Of course  3.fxe5  is not playable due to  3...Qh4  winning. After  3.Nf3  exf4  White has nothing better than transposing to the main line with exd5. }
3... exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Here White has some alternatives, but none seems particularly challenging for Black. If the knight captures on d5, Black will get an excellent position. }
5. c4 { Perhaps the best option. Even Carlsen has played this! } 5... c6
{ Again Black surrenders the pawn for good to speed development. } 6. dxc6
{ A weak move, just speeding Black's development. Let's see how we can counter it. }
6... Nxc6
{ If Black takes control of d4 the game is over, so White's play is practically forced. }
7. d4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 O-O
{ Black is ahead on development and ...Bg4 is coming next, with pressure on d4. }
