[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 { The famous Scotch Gambit. } 4... Bc5
{ Here the main line is by far  5.c3  and after  5...Nf6  we would transpose to the c3-d4 Italian, which will be covered inanother section. That is why I prefer playing this, rather than  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/2BpP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , which is the main option. As we will need to study this line anyway against the Italian, it makes no sense at all to learn 4...Nf6 as well. Fully learning one line is better than half-learning two! Let us check the two alternatives we need to be well prepared against. }
5. O-O d6 6. c3 Bg4
{ An important move, preventing the capture on d4 and stopping White's development. }
7. Qb3
{ The only way to fight for some initiative. Keep in mind White is a pawn down. }
7... Bxf3 8. gxf3 Ne5
{ Hitting the bishop and protecting f7. Next, Black can complete their development with ...Nf6 and ...O-O. }
*

