1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  would transpose to theFour Knights. } 5... bxc6 6. Qe2
{ A rare move, but still important to know. } 6... Rb8
{ Black has some alternatives, but I like this move. We put some pressure on b2 and control the b4-square. This is an important square for Black's pieces, as we will see. }
7. e5 Nd5 8. c4 { If  8.Nd2  we simply play  8...Be7  intending ...O-O. } 8...
Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Nf4
{ Now the power of the rook on b8 becomes apparent: it covers the b4-bishop and applies some indirect pressure on b2. }
10. Qe3 Ng6
{ Black will play ...O-O and ...Re8 next to put pressure on e5, with a great position. }
