1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  would transpose tothe Four Knights. } 5... bxc6 6. e5
{ The main move. } 6... Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ This move has recently become very popular and we should be ready to face it. }
8... Qe6
{ Black prepares to develop their bishop and castle.  8...d6  is also possible. }
9. Nd2 a5
{ A very useful move that has lots of merits. First, it allows Ba6 and secures the b4-square for the knight or the bishop. As White's plan usually involves a c4 + b3 pawn formation, a potential a4 push may be quite challenging to face. }
10. g3
{ After  10.c4  Nb6  , Black would follow up with Bb4 with strong pressure on the queenside. }
10... Nb4
{ Black starts to create threats in order to weaken White's position. } 11. Nf3
Ba6 12. c4 Qg6 { Aiming once again at the light squares. } 13. Kd1 c5
{ With the idea of freeing the c6-square for the knight in case of a3. This is a complex position, but harder to play for White, as their king has lost castling rights and is stuck in the center. In his Chessable course, Sethuraman tries to justify White's play with this follow-up: }
*

