1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  would transpose to theFour Knights. } 5... bxc6 6. e5
{ The main move. } 6... Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4 Ba6
{ Exploiting the pin.  8...Nb6  is also possible. } 9. b3 g6
{ This is the main position in this line. White has different moves here and they are all dangerous. }
10. g3 { This move leads almost by force to a well-known endgame. } 10... Bg7
11. Bb2 O-O 12. Bg2 Rae8 { 12...Rfe8  is similar. } 13. O-O Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxe5
15. Qxe5 Rxe5 16. cxd5 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 cxd5 18. Nc3 { 18.Na3  is similar. } 18...
c6
{ And we have reached this unbalanced yet equal endgame. Black has a rook and two pawns, whereas White has a knight and a bishop. I will analyze this position in more detail in the video. Here is an overview of the most important ideas:  • We need to centralize our king; d6 is usually a good square.  • We should trade one rook if possible, and we should not allow White's rook to comfortably reach the a6-square. How? Either by threatening a rook invasion through the e-file or by pushing ...a5 and placing a rook on a8. Then White's rook would stand on the not so annoying a4-square. }
