1. e4 e5
{ Against both  2.Nc3  and  2.Bc4  , we need to be aware of transpositions. White can always get us back to a main line by playing Nf3. }
2. Nc3 Nc6
{ After  3.Nf3  Nf6  we would reach theFour Knights which we will examine in another chapter,   and after  3.Bc4  Nf6  , White has no choice but to transpose to the main line with 4.d3 or to the Italian with 4.Nf3. }
3. f4
{ This transposes to a King's Gambit in an improved version for Black. This move is not really worth our time, but we can check the most straightforward line, which can be seen in a lot of games. }
3... exf4 4. Nf3 g5 5. h4 g4 6. Ng5 h6 7. Nxf7 Kxf7 8. Bc4+ d5
{ Protecting the g4-pawn with our bishop. White has no compensation for the piece. }
*

