1. e4 e5 2. d4
{ This move goes against chess principles but still, it can be quite dangerous. GM Nepomniachtchi has used it several times in rapid games and the idea is to develop the whole queenside and then castle long. }
2... exd4 3. Qxd4 Nc6 4. Qe3 Nf6
{ Black develops normally. The idea is to castle quickly and try to play ...Re8 to punish White for having the queen on e3. }
5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Bd2 O-O 7. O-O-O Re8
{ Black's position is already very good because the queen on e3 is badly placed. We are threatening ...d5 and White will have to sacrifice the e4-pawn in order to try and get some activity. }
8. Qg3 Nxe4
{ 8...Rxe4  is also good, but I think this one is better and simpler. } 9. Nxe4
Rxe4 10. Bf4
{ Maybe this is the best try, but Black will be much better with correct play. }
10... Qf6
{ Attacking f4 and, as we will see, targeting the queenside as well. } 11. Nh3
{ A sad necessity, but the bishop must be defended. } 11... d6 12. Bd3 Nd4
{ Taking advantage of the fact that  13.Bxe4  is not possible because of  13...Ne2  . White's position is close to collapse and Bxh3  is a threat. }
13. Kb1
{ The most usual move and the one that 'Nepo' played but, as we are about to see, he was crushed.  13.Be3  was the only move to hold and Black would have several good replies such as  13...Nf5  or  13...Bc5  . }
13... Ne2 14. Qf3 Ba3 { Forcing to take and giving the square to the knight. }
