[Black "Giuoco Pianissimo, 6.b4 Bb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6
{ We will now examine some lines that are not that usual in current tournament practice. However, they are still reasonable choices and played from time to time. }
6. b4
{ Gaining some space on the queenside. The flip side is some weakening and more potential breakthroughs for Black. }
6... Bb6 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2 Ne7
{ Black follows the standard plan of regrouping the knight to g6 and playing for ...c6 and ...d5. }
9. Bb3 c6
{ Playing for ...d5, but also freeing the c7-square for the bishop in the event of Nc4. }
10. Nc4 Bc7
{ Black follows the usual plan. If we can manage to get ...d5 in, the c4-knight will cause White to lose some tempi. }
11. Bg5 Ng6 { Threatening ...h6. } 12. Nh4
{ The only way to stop ...h6, but the knight is awkward on h4. } 12... Nf4
{ Black will play ...h6 next, trading the dark-squared bishop, and will try to push ...d5. White's pieces are very poorly placed. }
*

