1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6
{ We will now examine some lines that are not that usual in current tournament practice. However, they are still reasonable choices and played from time to time. }
6. b4
{ Gaining some space on the queenside. The flip side is some weakening and more potential breakthroughs for Black. }
6... Bb6 7. a4 a5
{ White cannot be allowed to push a5, as that would trap the b6-bishop. } 8. b5
Ne7 { The knight is heading to g6 again. } 9. O-O O-O 10. Nbd2
{ White intends to regroup this knight to c4 to hit the b6-bishop, so Black takes some preemptive measures. }
