1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6
{ We will now examine some lines that are not that usual in current tournament practice. However, they are still reasonable choices and played from time to time. }
6. Bg5
{ I have examined 7.Bg5 after 6.O-O in more detail inanother section of the course. Here White has not castled yet, so there are some differences. }
6... h6 7. Bh4 a6
{ Now a setup with a5 is more dangerous than playing a6 instead, as White could eventually castle queenside and then Black's lack of control of the b5-square would not allow us to launch an attack on that side of the board. }
8. Nbd2 Ba7
{ Black puts their bishop to safety, pre-empting potential d4 or b4 pushes. }
9. a4
{ Gaining some space on the queenside and stopping the Na5 idea, that would trade the c4-bishop in some lines. }
9... g5 10. Bg3 Qe7
{ Delaying castle allows Black to execute other plans now. } 11. b4 Nh5
{ Black has made more progress on the kingside than White on the queenside.  12.b5  is simply met by  12...Na5  . }
*

