1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6
{ We will now examine some lines that are not that usual in current tournament practice. However, they are still reasonable choices and played from time to time. }
6. O-O a5 7. Bb3
{ The point of this move is a potential regroup of the bishop to c2 and then pushing d4. It is more natural when Black plays 6...a6, but we should know how to handle it here as well. That will help us understand these positions. }
7... O-O 8. Re1 Be6
{ Black is happy to trade these bishops, as the position would be simplified and easier to play for Black. Therefore, retreating the b3-bishop is the most sensible option for White. }
9. Ba4
{ White has lost several tempi, but their plan is to push d4 and we need to be precise. }
9... Bb6 10. Nbd2 Ne7
{ Black lifts some pressure off d4, but transfers the knight to the kingside, where it guards the e5-pawn and may eventually join the attack. Also, White's a4-bishop loses its purpose. }
11. d4 Ng6 12. h3
{ If  12.Nf1  Black has  12...Bg4  , so White cannot do without this move. }
12... Nh5 { The knight is eyeing the f4-square. } 13. Nf1 Nhf4 14. Ng3 exd4
{ Without the knight on f6, this move is an option for Black because, as we will see, later on a breakthrough with the f-pawn will be available. }
15. Nxd4
{ 15.cxd4  d5=  16.e5  f6∓  Black has some nice pressure on the center and the kingside, and the rook on f8 secures the f4-knight. }
