{ We will now examine some lines that are not that usual in current tournament practice. However, they are still reasonable choices and played from time to time. }
6. O-O a5 7. Bb3
{ The point of this move is a potential regroup of the bishop to c2 and then pushing d4. It is more natural when Black plays 6...a6, but we should know how to handle it here as well. That will help us understand these positions. }
7... O-O 8. Re1 Be6
{ Black is happy to trade these bishops, as the position would be simplified and easier to play for Black. Therefore, retreating the b3-bishop is the most sensible option for White. }
9. Bc2 Ng4 { Hitting f2 and forcing White to lose a tempo. } 10. d4
{ This natural move fails to some tactics.  10.Re2  d5  11.exd5?!  Bxd5∓  Threatening ...Bxf3 with a good position for Black.    10.Rf1  d5!  Black breaks first in the center and secures the initiative.  11.h3  dxe4  . }
