7. Bb3
{ The point of this move is a potential regroup of the bishop to c2 and then pushing d4. It is more natural when Black plays 6...a6, but we should know how to handle it here as well. That will help us understand these positions. }
7... O-O 8. Re1 Be6
{ Black is happy to trade these bishops, as the position would be simplified and easier to play for Black. Therefore, retreating the b3-bishop is the most sensible option for White. }
9. Bc2 Ng4 { Hitting f2 and forcing White to lose a tempo. } 10. Rf1 d5
{ Black gets to break first in the center and secures the initiative. } 11.
exd5
{ White was not in time to play  11.h3  due to  11...dxe4  with an excellent position. }
11... Qxd5 12. h3 Nf6 13. Nbd2 h6
{ Black has taken over the center and has more space for their pieces. Next, Black can play ...Rad8 and ...Rfe8 with better prospects in the middlegame. }
