1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans Gambit! Not a usual sight nowadays, but good to know how to handle it. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Be7
{ Recently, the most usual move, with good reason. Black sidesteps the sharpest lines and simply wants to return the pawn to develop quickly. }
6. d4 Na5
{ An important move, kicking the bishop away from c4. Black offers the e5-pawn to get some initiative. }
7. Bd3 d6 { Black gives the pawn back to speed development. } 8. dxe5 dxe5 9.
Nxe5 Nf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2
{ Other moves do not change much in the position. For example,  11.Qe2  Re8  with a similar position. }
11... Bd6
{ Black has several options here. This is perhaps the most straightforward continuation. }
12. Nf3 Bg4 { Attacking the knight again. } 13. Nbd2 Re8
{ Thus Black has prevented the development of the c1-bishop. } 14. h3 Bh5 15.
Re1 Nd7
{ Controlling e5 and heading to c5, an excellent outpost for Black's pieces. }
