1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans Gambit! Not a usual sight nowadays, but good to know how to handle it. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Be7
{ Recently, the most usual move, with good reason. Black sidesteps the sharpest lines and simply wants to return the pawn to develop quickly. }
6. d4 Na5
{ An important move, kicking the bishop away from c4. Black offers the e5-pawn to get some initiative. }
7. Be2 d6
{ Again, the idea is to return the e5-pawn and win some tempi. If now  8.O-O  Nc6  Black is in time to protect the pawn, so White has to take now. }
8. Qa4+ c6 { Guarding the a5-knight. } 9. dxe5
{ If  9.O-O  Black plays  9...Qc7  protecting the e5-pawn. } 9... dxe5 10. Nxe5
Nf6 { Black continues developing and White has no threats at all. } 11. O-O Qc7
12. f4
{ 12.Bf4  is met by  12...Bd6  ,   whereas if  12.Nf3  then  12...O-O  . }
12... O-O
{ White's e4- and f4-pawns control some good squares, but their coordination with the rest of pieces is awful. The e5-knight stands in the way and the queenside is underdeveloped, so Black has a good position. }
