[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4
{ This move is still often played nowadays, so it is essential for Black to know it well. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4
{ This move is less and less seen, as it appears that Black is fine in the main lines. }
6... Bb4+ 7. Nc3
{ White sacrifices the e4-pawn to get some extra tempi, but Black is just one move away from castling, so White's compensation is insufficient. }
7... Nxe4 8. O-O Bxc3 9. d5
{ This is White's idea. After  9.bxc3  d5  , Black has a healthy extra pawn. }
9... Bf6
{ White will get the piece back. However, Black will be perfectly fine if they can safely castle. }
10. Re1
{ After  10.dxc6  bxc6  , Black will play ...d5 supporting e4, with a huge advantage. }
10... Ne7 11. Rxe4 d6
{ 11...O-O  is also possible, but Black can take some time to prevent the d6 push first. }
12. g4 { A desperate attempt to disturb Black's position. } 12... O-O 13. g5
Be5 { Black returns the pawn and will now target White's kingside weaknesses. }
*

