{ This move is less and less seen, as it appears that Black is fine in the main lines. }
6... Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2
{ Again White sacrifices a pawn to try and get some initiative. } 8... Nxe4 9.
d5 Ne7 10. Bb4 { Avoiding Nxd2 and threatening d6. } 10... d6
{ Black can take some time now: there are no more direct threats from White. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 Nc5
{ White has some compensation for the pawn because of the space advantage and the bishop pair, but of course, Black's position is better: the e7-knight will regroup to g6 and Black can easily go on with their development. }
*

