[White "Italian with 5.d4"]
[Black "Giuoco Piano, 5.d4 exd4 7.Bd2 Bxd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4
{ This move is still often played nowadays, so it is essential for Black to know it well. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4
{ This move is less and less seen, as it appears that Black is fine in the main lines. }
6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ { 7...Nxe4  is an interesting alternative. } 8. Nbxd2 d5
{ Black needs to play this move to prevent White's central pawns from rolling. }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Qb3 { This move is basically an attempt to make a draw. }
10... Na5 11. Qa4+ Nc6
{ The queen stands worse on a4 than on d1, as there is a potential Nb6 forking queen and bishop. Therefore, repetition is the best policy. }
12. Qb3 Nce7
{ Of course,  12...Na5  led to a repetition, but this is totally playable to keep the game on. White has some pressure on d5 and b7 and will reach the e-file first. However, Black has enough defensive chances and may get the upper hand in the long run thanks to the isolated d4-pawn. }
*

