{ This move is still often played nowadays, so it is essential for Black to know it well. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4
{ This move is less and less seen, as it appears that Black is fine in the main lines. }
6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ { 7...Nxe4  is an interesting alternative. } 8. Nbxd2 d5
{ Black needs to play this move to prevent White's central pawns from rolling. }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. O-O O-O
{ This position is equal and practice has shown that White even needs to be more careful here, as the d4-pawn is potentially weak. }
11. Rc1
{ The best try. Black wanted to play Nb6 intending Nxd4. Now after  11...Nb6  12.Bb3  , if Black takes on d4, White's rook will capture c7. }
11... Re8 12. Re1 { After  12.Bb5  Bd7  , Black is perfectly fine. } 12...
Rxe1+ 13. Qxe1 Nce7
{ Black lifts some pressure off d4, but strengthens d5 and will develop the rest of the pieces. }
