{ This move is still often played nowadays, so it is essential for Black to know it well. }
5... exd4 6. e5 d5 7. Bb5 { The main move. } 7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. Nc3 O-O
10. Be3 { It is important for White to keep the d4-pawn well protected. } 10...
Bg4 { Pinning the f3-knight, in charge of the defense of d4 and e5. } 11. h3
Bh5
{ Now  12.Qc2  is by far the most played move, but I will examine some alternatives. Despite not being so popular, these moves are interesting as well and worth knowing. }
12. O-O Nxd4
{ This tactical motif is also present in the main line. White's overload on d4 and f3 is exploited by Black to rip open White's castle and seek a perpetual. }
13. Bxd4 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qg5+ 15. Kh1 Qf5
{ This is the point: White is a piece up, but their king is exposed and has no way to avoid the perpetual. }
16. fxe4 Qxh3+ 17. Kg1 Bxd4
{ Black's threats include Bxe5 and Qg3+, so taking on d4 is forced. } 18. Qxd4
Qg4+ 19. Kh1 Qh4+ { And again we see a draw by repetition. } *

