[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Italian with Bg5"]
[Black "Giuoco Pianissimo, 7.Bg5 h6 ... 11.Bb3 Kg7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O a5 7. Bg5
{ Obviously, the most aggressive choice for White in the Italian, leading to extremely complex positions. It is also possible to transpose with  7.Re1  O-O  8.Bg5  , which will soon lead to the same position. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 { The only way to break the annoying pin on f6. } 9. Bg3 O-O
{ Black's king may look potentially more exposed, but Black's pieces have good central control. If White is not allowed to open up the position with d4, Black will manage to transfer more pieces to the kingside and launch an attack there. }
10. Nbd2 Ba7 11. Bb3 Kg7
{ This move is quite useful in these positions. The king steps away from the a2-g8, thus avoiding White's bishop, and guards h6. In some lines, this allows ...Nh5, which usually fails to Nxe5 and Qxh5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Italian with Bg5"]
[Black "Giuoco Pianissimo, 7.Bg5 h6 ... 11.Bb3 Kg7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O a5 7. Bg5
{ Obviously, the most aggressive choice for White in the Italian, leading to extremely complex positions. It is also possible to transpose with  7.Re1  O-O  8.Bg5  , which will soon lead to the same position. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 { The only way to break the annoying pin on f6. } 9. Bg3 O-O
{ Black's king may look potentially more exposed, but Black's pieces have good central control. If White is not allowed to open up the position with d4, Black will manage to transfer more pieces to the kingside and launch an attack there. }
10. Nbd2 Ba7 11. Bb3
{ White is trying to regroup their knight via c4-e3.  11.Re1  would transpose to the main line. }
11... Kg7
{ This move is quite useful in these positions. The king steps away from the a2-g8, thus avoiding White's bishop, and guards h6. In some lines, this allows ...Nh5, which usually fails to Nxe5 and Qxh5. }
12. Nc4 Ne7
{ Black intends to regroup this knight to g6, where it will support the e5-pawn and may jump to f4. }
13. Nxa5
{ Grabbing this pawn is not a good idea; Black gains some tempi for the attack.  13.Ne3  Bxe3  14.fxe3  Ng6=  The position will remain closed, and Black's knights are superior to White's bishops. }
13... Nh5 14. Nc4 f5
{ Black's attack is extremely powerful. All the black pieces, except the a8-rook, can easily join the attack. The a7-bishop, pointed at f2, will be a nightmare for White. }
*

