1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O a5 7. Bg5
{ Obviously, the most aggressive choice for White in the Italian, leading to extremely complex positions. It is also possible to transpose with  7.Re1  O-O  8.Bg5  , which will soon lead to the same position. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 { The only way to break the annoying pin on f6. } 9. Bg3 O-O
{ Black's king may look potentially more exposed, but Black's pieces have good central control. If White is not allowed to open up the position with d4, Black will manage to transfer more pieces to the kingside and launch an attack there. }
10. Re1
{ After  10.a4  Kg7  play is similar to the lines we will examine here and having the king on g7 looks more useful than having the pawn on a4. }
10... Ba7 { Pre-empting d4. Now White's b1-knight has two available routes. }
11. Nbd2 Nh7
{ Intending ...h5. Black's h- and g-pawns will harass White's pieces, which are running short of squares. }
12. h3 h5 13. d4
{ White needs to go for the central break. This move also blocks the a7-bishop for the moment. After  13.Nf1  Qf6  Black would obtain a great position. }
13... h4
{ Opening the center is not an option, so Black keeps on putting pressure on the kingside instead. }
14. Bh2 g4 15. hxg4 Bxg4
{ The pressure on f3 and d4 is uncomfortable for White. Besides, Black has completed development and is ready for a timely exd4 at some point. }
16. Be2 Qf6 { Increasing the pressure on d4. } 17. Nc4
{ Taking on e5 is not good, as it opens the scope of the a7-bishop. Therefore, White offers the d4-pawn to open up the position and tries to improve their pieces. }
17... exd4 18. e5 Qg7
{ The queen is perfectly placed on g7, guarding Black's king and preparing to target g2 with the ...h3 push. }
19. cxd4 h3 20. Ne3
{ The best way to protect g2, but the e5-pawn loses some support. } 20... dxe5
21. Nxe5
{ After  21.Nxg4  Qxg4  , Black is threatening mate on g2, which forces White to waste yet another tempo. }
21... Bxe2 22. Qxe2 Bxd4
{ 22...Nxd4  is also a fine option, but after  23.Qh5  White gets some activity and a complicated game. }
23. Nxc6 bxc6 24. Bxc7 Bxe3 25. fxe3 Rae8
{ The immediate threat is Rxe3. If White manages to stop it, Black will play Re6-g6 with a strong attack and a safer king. }
