[Black "Giuoco Pianissimo, 5.d4 d6 6.O-O a5 ... 11.Ng3 a4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O a5
{ Stopping White's b4-expansion and freeing the a7-square for the bishop to stay out of harm's way. }
7. Re1 O-O
{ White's plan is regrouping the b1-knight to g3 and try to push d4. This may or may not include playing h3. }
8. Nbd2 Ba7 { Pre-empting a potential d4 push. } 9. Nf1 Be6
{ Black wants to trade bishops and now White is forced to make an important decision. }
10. Bxe6 { This is a double-edged move and not all White players' cup of tea. }
10... fxe6
{ Black has doubled pawns, but now the f -file is open so that the rook and the a7-bishop launch an excellent combined attack against f2. Black will enjoy very active piece play. }
11. Ng3 a4
{ Again Black gains some space and takes the b3-square away from White's queen. }
12. h3 { Preventing an eventual Ng4. } 12... h6 13. d4 exd4 14. cxd4 Bb6
{ Black improves their bishop, freeing the way for the a8-rook. White has managed to push d4, but the c1-bishop lacks good squares and Black has different ways to attack White's center. }
15. Be3
{ If White played some waiting move, for example  15.a3  Black could reply  15...Qe8  with ideas like Nh5. }
15... d5 16. e5 Ne4
{ White cannot really take on e4, as then the d4-pawn would drop, so Black has a nice position. }
