[Black "Giuoco Pianissimo, 5.d4 d6 6.O-O a5 ... 11.Nf1 Ng6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O a5
{ Stopping White's b4-expansion and freeing the a7-square for the bishop to stay out of harm's way. }
7. Re1 O-O
{ White's plan is regrouping the b1-knight to g3 and try to push d4. This may or may not include playing h3. }
8. h3 Ba7 { Again saving the bishop before the d4 push comes. } 9. Nbd2 Be6 10.
Bb5
{ After  10.Bxe6  fxe6  11.Nf1  we would end up reachingthe same line we have examined under 8.Nbd2. }
10... Ne7
{ Once again, the knight is heading to g6 allowing White to push d4, but setting up a central and kingside attack. }
11. Nf1
{ White has no time for slowly preparing the d4 push, because Black gets to play d5 first, as we will see. }
11... Ng6 12. Ng3 c6 13. Ba4 d5
{ This move is granted by a typical tactical motif: the e5-pawn is indirectly protected. }
14. exd5 Nxd5
{ An important move that allows the following tactical resource. } 15. d4
{ The natural move once the capture on e5 does not work, but Black already has better pieces. }
15... exd4 16. Nxd4 Qc7
{ Freeing the way for the rooks and setting up the following trap. } 17. Nxe6
{ Black's position is already better, but this move is just losing. } 17...
Bxf2+
{ Same move, but a different idea: now the g3-knight will be unprotected. } 18.
Kxf2 fxe6+ 19. Kg1 Qxg3 { With some extra material and a winning position. } *

