{ The key move. Instead of retreating the knight from e4, Black trades the f3-knight to weaken the d4-pawn. }
16. Nxh4 Qxh4 17. Nxe4 dxe4
{ Black simply wants to play ...Rad8 next, and then ...c5 picking up the d4-pawn, so White needs some concrete play here. }
18. g3 Qxh3 19. Rxe4 Rad8
{ 19...Bd5  is interesting too, but this move puts pressure on d4 and plans a beautiful combination. }
20. Be3
{ 20.Bf1  Qf5  21.Rh4  Qg6=  The point is to answer Bd3 with ...Bf5. Black wants to continue with ...c5 picking up the d4-pawn. }
20... Bd5 21. Bf1
{ Only move to deflect the queen before retreating the rook. } 21... Qe6 22.
Rh4 f5
{ Blocking the b1-h7 diagonal. Then White's attack would vanish and the rook is awkward on h4. }
23. Bd3 h6
{ Black can continue with ...Rd7 intending to double rooks and then go after the d4-pawn. }
*

