[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish Exchange"]
[Black "Spanish Exchange: 7.Bg5 Qd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6
{ A rare guest in top tournaments, as practice has shown that Black is perfectly fine in this line. Still, it is important to know this type of position, where a structure with doubled c-pawns arise. }
4... dxc6 5. O-O
{ 5.Nxe5  is not possible due to  5...Qd4  and Black gets the pawn back with a better position. }
5... Qf6
{ Besides 5...Qf6, other moves have been tried here, but I like this one best, and some top players have played it. }
6. d4
{ White needs to play active after giving up one of their bishops for a quicker development. }
6... exd4 7. Bg5 Qd6
{ It may look like White is developing their whole army, while Black is just moving their queen around. However, Black will always have a good grip on light squares, which leaves us out of trouble. Also, Black just needs to develop the c8-bishop and will be ready to castle queenside. }
8. Nxd4 Be7 { 8...Bd7  is also a good alternative. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish Exchange"]
[Black "Spanish Exchange: 7.Bg5 Qd6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6
{ A rare guest in top tournaments, as practice has shown that Black is perfectly fine in this line. Still, it is important to know this type of position, where a structure with doubled c-pawns arise. }
4... dxc6 5. O-O
{ 5.Nxe5  is not possible due to  5...Qd4  and Black gets the pawn back with a better position. }
5... Qf6
{ Besides 5...Qf6, other moves have been tried here, but I like this one best, and some top players have played it. }
6. d4
{ White needs to play active after giving up one of their bishops for a quicker development. }
6... exd4 7. Bg5 Qd6
{ It may look like White is developing their whole army, while Black is just moving their queen around. However, Black will always have a good grip on light squares, which leaves us out of trouble. Also, Black just needs to develop the c8-bishop and will be ready to castle queenside. }
8. Nxd4 Be7 { 8...Bd7  is also a good alternative. } 9. Bxe7 Nxe7 10. Nc3 Bd7
{ Setting up queenside castling. This way our king will be safer, guarded by four pawns in front of him, and we can push our kingside pawns. }
11. Nb3 { 11.Nde2  does not fundamentally change this position. } 11... O-O-O
{ The endgame would be balanced, so usually White tries to keep the queens alive. }
12. Qe2 Ng6 13. Rad1 Qe7 14. Qe3 { Threatening Qa7. } 14... Kb8
{ With an equal position. White's plan is trading rooks and queens off to play the endgame, and Black has to prevent this: we' will trade just one pair of rooks and intend something like ...Ne5 and ...g5 trying to get some kingside play. If White plays f4 at some point, then we will go for ...Re8 putting pressure on e4, and regroup our knight via f8. }
*

