1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6
{ A rare guest in top tournaments, as practice has shown that Black is perfectly fine in this line. Still, it is important to know this type of position, where a structure with doubled c-pawns arise. }
4... dxc6 5. Nc3
{ This is understandably much less played. White loses some options, like playing c3-d4. }
5... f6
{ As White lacks their light-squared bishop, we can happily play this move without worrying about a potential Bc4. }
6. d4 { The only breakthrough. } 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 8. Nde2 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Be6
{ These endgames are favorable to Black thanks to the bishop pair. White has some compensation in the fact that their kingside majority is more mobile, but my assessment @@StartBracket@@and the engine's!@@EndBracket@@ is that Black even has good chances of getting the upper hand. }
