[White "Spanish 5.d3 Bc5"]
[Black "Spanish, Anderssen Variation: 6.Bxc6 dxc6 7.O-O Qe7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 6. Bxc6 dxc6
{ We have reached this typical Berlin position, where the only difference is that our pawn is on a6. This detail favours Black, as it secures the a7-square for our bishop. }
7. O-O { Now Nxe5 is already a threat. } 7... Qe7
{ If  7...Bg4  White has  8.h3  Bh5  9.g4  with the idea of taking on e5. } 8.
Nbd2 Bg4 { We develop our bishop before playing ...Nd7. } 9. Nc4 Nd7 10. h3 Bh5
{ All Black's pieces are well placed and we can choose castling kingside or queenside at our convenience. }
11. Be3 Bxe3
{ 11...Bd6  is passive, our bishop stands really awkward on d6 blocked by our own pawns, whereas White's e3-bishop would eye both flanks. Therefore, we better trade it off, as otherwise we would allow White to take the initiative and equalize. }
12. Nxe3 O-O-O
{ Black's king will be really safe behind that pawn wall and our kingside attack is coming. }
*

