1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 6. Bxc6 dxc6
{ We have reached this typical Berlin position, where the only difference is that our pawn is on a6. This detail favours Black, as it secures the a7-square for our bishop. }
7. Nbd2 { The most usual move. White can still castle queenside. } 7... Qe7
{ 7...Ng4!?  is a very interesting and tricky idea I have played in several games. For those aggressive players who may be interested, I recommend to check my games against Aronian and Naiditsch. Here I will offer the most solid alternative, which offers Black an easy game. }
8. Nc4 Nd7 9. Qe2
{ Castling queenside is not so logical, as Black has not castled yet. } 9... f6
10. Bd2 Nf8 11. O-O-O Be6
{ Black prepares long castle, with a very nice position. } *

