7. Nbd2 { The most usual move. White can still castle queenside. } 7... Qe7
{ 7...Ng4!?  is a very interesting and tricky idea I have played in several games. For those aggressive players who may be interested, I recommend to check my games against Aronian and Naiditsch. Here I will offer the most solid alternative, which offers Black an easy game. }
8. Nc4 Nd7 9. O-O O-O
{ If White castles kingside, we follow suit. Now White has many different approaches, but Black will always follow a similar plan: regrouping the knight to g6 or e6 via f8-square. }
10. c3
{ White intends d4, but this is not challenging for Black and just opens up the position for our bishop pair. }
10... Re8 11. Re1 Ba7 12. d4 exd4 13. cxd4 Nf8
{ Next, Black will play ...Bg4 or ...Be6 and ...Rad8 putting pressure on White's center. }
