1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 6. c3
{ A natural move preparing d4.  6.O-O  d6  7.c3  O-O  Transposing to the main line. Skipping c3 makes no sense for White. }
6... d6 7. O-O O-O
{ Reaching an Italian-like position, but White's bishop stands on a4 instead of c4. Black's main idea is regrouping the knight to g6 via e7. }
8. Re1 Ba7
{ This move is always important: we should not allow White getting d4 in with a tempo. }
9. Bg5
{ This move is not so logical without the bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal. } 9...
h6 10. Bh4 g5
{ 11.Bxg5  hxg5  12.Nxg5  is met by  12...Ng4  and Black is in charge. } 11.
Nxg5 { This sacrifice rarely works, and this position is no exception. } 11...
hxg5 12. Bxg5 Bg4
{ Black uses some tactical resources to prevent the queen joining the attack via f3. }
13. Bxf6 { 13.Qd2  is met by  13...Kh7!  intending ...Rg8-...g6. } 13... Bxd1
{ 13...Bxf2  is also good. } 14. Bxd8 Bxa4
{ The key. Black keeps the extra piece. } *

