[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 6. c3
{ A natural move preparing d4.  6.O-O  d6  7.c3  O-O  Transposing to the main line. Skipping c3 makes no sense for White. }
6... d6 7. O-O O-O
{ Reaching an Italian-like position, but White's bishop stands on a4 instead of c4. Black's main idea is regrouping the knight to g6 via e7. }
8. Re1 Ba7
{ This move is always important: we should not allow White getting d4 in with a tempo. }
9. Nbd2 Ne7 { According to plan. Black gets faster. } 10. Nf1 Ng6 11. Ng3 d5
{ Our central break comes first. } 12. Bg5
{ 12.exd5  Qxd5  13.Bb3  Qd6=  And Black has everything under control. Next we will develop our c8-bishop and place our rooks on central files. }
12... h6
{ A thematic pawn sacrifice that gives Black an excellent position.  ­ } 13.
Bxf6 Qxf6 14. exd5 Bg4
{ The pin on f3 is really unpleasant and, after the capture, Black's knight will enjoy some great squares on f4 or h4. }
