1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Qe2
{ This move gives room for the rook and presses the knight on e4 @@StartBracket@@after Nbd2@@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Be7 10. Rd1
{ The main move. The idea is to press on d5 and play c4 taking advantage of the pinning. }
10... O-O 11. c4
{ After  11.c3  f5  12.exf6  Bxf6  we would probably end up transposing to the line that starts with 10.Nbd2. }
11... bxc4 12. Bxc4
{ White has strong pressure on d5 and Black needs to play concrete to solve the problem. }
12... Bc5 13. Be3 { Unique to defend f2. } 13... Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Qb8
{ Black gets out of the pinning while threatening b2 and forcing White's next move. }
15. Bb3 Na5
{ Attacking b3 and freeing the c pawn. Black is holding without much trouble in this position but there are some forced lines to be aware of. }
16. Nbd2 Qa7
{ Forcing an ending where Black should hold without much trouble. Against Nxe4 there is always the intermezzo Nxb3. Let's look at the lines that have been played the most. }
17. Qxa7 Rxa7 18. Rac1 c5
{ Important move not to let white block the delayed pawn. } 19. Nxe4 Nxb3 20.
axb3 dxe4 21. Nd2 e3 22. fxe3 Rb7
{ The entire queenside is going to be liquidated with draw. } *

