1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Be3 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Nbd2
{ Here we reach the typical position of this line with 9.Be3. Black has several alternatives and here I will analyze only 11...Qd7 because I like the resulting type of position, but both  11...Bg4  and  11...Nxd2  are playable as well. }
11... Qd7 12. Bc2 Nxd2 13. Qxd2 Bg4
{ Tying up the knight on f3 that is defending e5. This pawn is going to suffer a bit if White does not play precise. }
14. Qd3
{ 14.Bf4  it is possible but after  14...Bxf3  15.gxf3  Black can decide between several moves like Rad8 or Nd8 with idea of Ne6, interesting play. }
14... g6 { Avoiding mate on h7 and allowing Bf5 on some lines. } 15. Bh6 Rfe8
16. Rae1
{ Interestingly it is very important to put this rook and not the f1 rook since now 16...Bf8 is not so good, since after the line mentioned in 16.Rfe1 would exist the move 24.Rxf6+ winning. }
16... Rad8
{ Putting the last missing piece in the center and supporting the d4 break. }
17. Qe3
{ Looking to take the queen to f4 where it defends e5 and controls the black squares. }
17... Bf6
{ Taking advantage of the pinning to bring the bishop to h8 where it controls g7 and f6 and presses on e5. }
18. Qf4 Bh8 19. Nd4
{ Black threatened Bxf3 followed by Nxe5. This move based on tactical themes is unique for trying to create problems for Black. }
19... Nxe5
{ Of course  20...Bxe5  not good because of  21.Rxe5  followed by Qf6 and Qg7. }
20. h3 { Now the bishop is trapped but Black has resources. } 20... c5 21. Nb3
Bf5 22. Bxf5 { 22.Nxc5  was answered with  22...Qc8  and ...Qxc5. } 22... Qxf5
23. Qxf5 gxf5 24. Nxc5 Rc8
{ White cannot play  25.Nxa6  because  25...Re6  . The knight on c4 together with the bishop on h8 are going to coordinate to attack the queenside so Black is no worse off. }
*

