1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Be7
{ Now White has several moves that transpose to main lines such as 10.Be3, 10.Qe2 or 10.Nbd2 that we have studied in other sections. After  10.Bc2  O-O  again the two options we have  11.Qe2  and  11.Nbd2  transposing to lines we have already analyzed. Let us then look at the other options. }
10. Re1 O-O 11. Nd4
{ This move is quite dangerous as we are going to see and black's moves are not easy at all. }
11... Nxe5 { Sacrificing a piece. } 12. f3 Bh4
{ It seems crazy but the lack of white development on the queenside, the activity of the black pieces and the control of the center makes it possible for this to work. }
13. g3 c5
{ Everything is in the air but White's lack of development combined with the weakness of the f3-square and the white king gives Black very good initiative. }
14. Nxe6
{ After  14.gxh4  Qxh4  , the attack would be devastating so this move is unique. }
14... fxe6
{ Now the f column is going to be a nightmare for white, Nxf3 is threatened. }
15. fxe4 c4 { Good intermezzo restricting the white bishop. } 16. Bc2 Bg5
{ Black has a piece less and quietly retires the bishop, but in exchange he still has a very good attack and with this move he prevents the logical development of the knight on d2. }
17. Kg2 { Avoiding ...Nf3+. } 17... Bxc1 18. Qxc1 d4 19. cxd4
{ After  19.Nd2  both  19...Ra7  to double on the f file and  19...Ng4  gave Black a good position. }
19... Qxd4 { Threatening input on f2. } 20. Re2 Nd3 21. Qd2 b4
{ Nice move taking the c3 square away from both knight and queen. White cannot move.  21...Qxb2  was not good because of  22.Qc3  . }
22. Bxd3 cxd3 23. Re3 Rac8 { Threatening Rc2.  23...Rad8  was also good. } 24.
Qe1
{ The only way not to lose since  24.Rxd3  was answered by  23....Qxe4   and  24.Qxd3  with  24...Qxb2  . }
24... Qxb2+ 25. Nd2 a5
{ 26.Rxd3  loses by  26...Rcd8  , so Black keeps the d3 pawn and can create another on the queenside with better winning chances. }
