[White "Open Spanish Main line 12.exf6"]
[Black "Open Spanish Main with 12.exf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. exf6
{ It is not the main one but I consider it one of the main ones and it is important to know it well. }
12... Nxf6
{ We arrive at a rather complex position, since no minor piece has been changed and there are different options. Let's look at the most dangerous ones. }
13. Re1 Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 15. Nf1
{ The idea Ng3 is annoying and Black needs to react. } 15... Bc5
{ Putting more pressure on the f file and 'avoiding'  16.Ng3  . } 16. Ng3
{ White can still play this move as Anish Giri played against me in the Magnus Invitational on chess24. }
16... Bxf3
{ Now the idea of Bc5 is understood. White cannot capture on f3 with the queen by Ne4 followed by Bxf2. }
17. gxf3
{ Despite the doubled pawns White has a good game thanks to the control of the white squares so you have to play precise. }
17... Ne7
{ Controlling f5 and allowing a possible c6 which overprotects d5. In my game with Giri I played  17...Qd6  and after some imprecise moves on my part White got a very good position. }
18. Bg5 { Preparing Qd3 and Bxf6. } 18... Qd7 19. Kg2
{ Of course  19.Qd3  not possible because  19...Qxh3  . } 19... Rf7
{ Preparing the dubbing in f and defending h7 indirectly as we shall see. } 20.
Qd3 Raf8 { 20...g6  not good because of  21.Bxf6  followed by Ne4 winning. }
21. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Black has managed to defend against threats and controls the f5-square. He can continue with ...Rh8 or ...c6 with an equal position. }
*

