1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. exf6
{ It is not the main one but I consider it one of the main ones and it is important to know it well. }
12... Nxf6
{ We arrive at a rather complex position, since no minor piece has been changed and there are different options. Let's look at the most dangerous ones. }
13. Re1 Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 15. Nf1
{ The idea Ng3 is annoying and Black needs to react. } 15... Bc5
{ Putting more pressure on the f file and 'avoiding'  16.Ng3  . } 16. Be3 d4
{ Black has everything perfectly in place for this move. } 17. cxd4 Nxd4
{ The pin on f3 forces the changes. } 18. Bxd4 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 Bxd4
{ Black has gained a strong bishop on d4 that points to both b2 and f2 and will also be well defended after the move ...c5. }
