1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. exf6
{ It is not the main one but I consider it one of the main ones and it is important to know it well. }
12... Nxf6
{ We arrive at a rather complex position, since no minor piece has been changed and there are different options. Let's look at the most dangerous ones. }
13. h3 { Avoiding the move Bg4. } 13... Qd7 14. Re1
{ 14.Ng5  did not make sense because of  14...Bf5  . } 14... Bd6
{ The bishop on d6 is better placed controlling e5 and also allows the following black move. }
15. Nf1 Ne4
{ Important move. It is not possible to capture everything on e4 because of the uncovered Bh2+ and Qxd1. In my game with Ganguly I played  15...Rae8  allowing  16.Ng3  and White was a bit better off. Now 16.Ng3 is not possible and the knight on e4 creates a lot of problems. }
16. Ng5 Nxg5 17. Bxg5 Kh8
{ Black prepares to play ...Bg8 defending the h7 point and has good control of the center and pressure on the f file. }
