1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3
{ The main line. White aims to get a knight into d4 by knocking on e6 and c6. }
12... Qd7 { Defending c6 and e6 and connecting rooks. } 13. Re1 Rad8 14. Qe2
{ Perhaps the only plan besides looking to put a knight on d4 is this move with a4 in mind. }
14... Bf7
{ One of the most common plans in this position. The bishop goes to h5 attacking the knight on f3 which is the only defender of the e5 pawn. }
15. a4 Bh5 16. axb5 axb5 17. e6
{ The only move that justifies white play. Otherwise the black position is very good. }
17... Qxe6 18. Nfd4
{ White manages to unpin and is going to recover the pawn. } 18... Nxd4 19.
Nxd4 Qg6 20. Qxb5 Bh4
{ Black threatens f2, and has a great initiative and attack on the kingside }
21. g3 Bxg3 22. hxg3 Nxg3
{ With probable repetition. The white king is weak but with correct play they should hold. }
