1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3
{ The main line. White aims to get a knight into d4 by knocking on e6 and c6. }
12... Qd7 { Defending c6 and e6 and connecting rooks. } 13. Qe1
{ A strange move but with a similar idea to  13.Re1  : put pressure on the e file and look for a better moment to put a knight on d4. }
13... Kh8
{ This move is also typical in these positions. The king will be safer and leaves the g8 square to the bishop.  13...Bf7  it was also possible with a similar idea. }
14. Nfd4 { With the ideas mentioned above. } 14... Nxe5 15. f3 Bg8 16. fxe4
fxe4
{ Again we come to this type of position where Black has two central pawns for the piece that greatly restrict the white pieces. It threatens ...Rxf1 followed by ...Rf8, and probably ...Qg4 with very good attack on the kingside; so White's move is unique in order not to stay worse off. }
17. Bf4 Nc4
{ Threatening ...Nxb2. It is difficult to play White;  18.Qg3  answered by  18...Rf6  with the idea of ...Rg6. }
18. Rb1 { It seems natural but White has no time to defend this pawn. } 18...
c5 19. Ne2 g5 20. Bg3 Rxf1+ 21. Qxf1 Rf8 22. Qe1 h5
{ Black's control is total. The white pieces have practically no squares and  23.h4  answered with  23...Qg4  with a devastating attack. }
