14. Nxd4
{ After  14.cxd4  a5  , White has no way to avoid a4 by displacing the knight from b3. }
14... c5 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3
{ If White does not push out this knight now, Black can follow up with ...c4 for Nc5. }
16... Ng5 17. Bxg5
{ This is White's other idea in this position. The different color bishops mean that White can make himself strong on squares of his color by pressing on d5 and f5, but the positions are quite equal and Black must hold with precise play. }
17... Bxg5 18. f4 Be7 19. Kh1 Rad8 20. b4
{ This idea proposed by the machine is interesting, but in practice I think black should be able to hold without much trouble. }
20... cxb4 21. cxb4 Bxb4 22. Bb3
{ White has given the b pawn but the d5 pawn is doomed. } 22... Qb6 23. Bxd5+
Kh8
{ White is a little better in this position, but Black can get strong on black squares and the likely major piece exchanges bring the draw closer. }
