[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3
{ The main line. White aims to get a knight into d4 by knocking on e6 and c6. }
12... Qd7 { Defending c6 and e6 and connecting rooks. } 13. Nfd4
{ 13.Nbd4  it is played more but after  13...Nxd4  14.Nxd4  it transposes to the main line and also gives an extra option to Black:  13...Nd8!?  , so more and more people are going for this move. }
13... Nxd4
{ 13...Nxe5  not possible because  14.f3  followed by Re1 and Black has too many pieces on the e file. }
14. Nxd4
{ After  14.cxd4  a5  , White has no way to avoid a4 by displacing the knight from b3. }
14... c5 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3
{ If White does not push out this knight now, Black can follow up with ...c4 for Nc5. }
16... Ng5 17. a4
{ Black has everything defended in the center, so White needs this plan to create problems. After  17.Kh1  f4  , White has nothing better to play  18.a4  back to the main line. }
17... Rad8 { Black gives up the file but in return defends his center better. }
18. axb5 axb5 19. Kh1 f4 { Limiting the bishop on c1 and avoiding White's f4. }
20. b4
{ By taking the c pawn away from Black, White seeks both to gain the d4-square and to play Bb3 by pressing on d4 without there being ...c4. }
20... c4
{ Both  20...cxb4  and  20...Qxe5  are playable as well, but I think this move gives Black better chances to get an advantage. Now White's bishops are very restricted and if White does not play precise, Black can look much better. }
21. Qd4
{ Defending e5 and avoiding d4. After a move like  21.Ra7  , Black can decide between playing  21...d4  or simply  21...Rde8  with the nice idea Bd8-b6. }
21... Qc6
{ Black threatens Ne6 with very good position so White needs to play concrete. }
22. Qa7 Qe6
{ Defending the e7 bishop and threatening e5 and d4 again. Of course  23.Qd4  would lead to repeated moves. }
23. Re1 d4 24. cxd4 { 24.Ra6  the answer was  24...Rd7  . } 24... Bxb4
{ The black pawns on the queenside are more dangerous than the white pawns in the center as these are well blocked. }
